1 deemed received from corporations if such dividends are included in federal taxable income. How-
2 ever:
3 (a) In the case of any dividend on debt-financed portfolio stock as described in section 246A of
4 the Internal Revenue Code, the subtraction allowed under this subsection shall be reduced under the
5 same conditions and in same amount as the dividends received deduction otherwise allowable for
6 federal income tax purposes is reduced under section 246A of the Internal Revenue Code.
7 (b) In the case of any dividend received from a 20 percent owned corporation, as defined in
8 section 243(c) of the Internal Revenue Code, or [global intangible low-taxed] net controlled foreign
9 corporation tested income included in gross income pursuant to section 951A of the Internal Re-
10 venue Code, this subsection shall be applied by substituting “80 percent” for “70 percent.”
11 (c) A dividend that is not treated as a dividend under section 243(d) of the Internal Revenue
12 Code may not be treated as a dividend for purposes of this subsection.
13 (d) If a dividends received deduction is not allowed for federal tax purposes because of section
14 246(a) or (c) of the Internal Revenue Code, a subtraction may not be made under this subsection for
15 received dividends that are described in section 246(a) or (c) of the Internal Revenue Code.
16 (e) In the case of any dividend received from an alien, domestic or foreign insurer, as defined
17 in ORS 731.082, that would be included in the taxpayer’s consolidated Oregon return but for the
18 application of ORS 317.710 (5) or (7), this subsection shall be applied by substituting “100 percent”
19 for “70 percent.”
20 (f) A subtraction under this subsection is not allowed for any amount of foreign-source dividend
21 income, as described in section 245A of the Internal Revenue Code, that is included in gross income.
22 (3) There shall be excluded from the sales factor of any apportionment formula employed to at-
23 tribute income to this state any amount subtracted from federal taxable income under subsection (2)
24 of this section or deducted under section 245A of the Internal Revenue Code. The amount of any
25 dividend or of any global intangible low-taxed income that is apportionable shall be determined as
26 provided by the apportionment formula applicable to the taxpayer, as provided in ORS 314.280 and
27 314.605 to 314.675, but may not include any amount subtracted under subsection (2) of this section.
28 SECTION 3. Section 32a, chapter 579, Oregon Laws 2019, is amended to read:
29 Sec. 32a. The amendments to ORS 315.266 by section 31, chapter 579, Oregon Laws 2019, [of
30 this 2019 Act] apply to tax years beginning on or after January 1, 2020[, and before January 1,
31 2026].
32 SECTION 4. ORS 284.368 is amended to read:
33 284.368. (1) As used in this section:
34 (a) “Actual Oregon expenses” means the costs paid in Oregon for principal photography, pro-
35 duction or postproduction in Oregon of a film, or for media production services, including but not
36 limited to the purchase or rental cost of equipment, food, lodging, real property and permits and
37 payments made for salaries, wages and benefits for work in Oregon.
38 (b) “Film” means a television movie or one or more episodes of a single television series, [or]
39 a movie produced for release to theaters, video or the Internet or a commercial. “Film” does not
40 include the production of [a commercial or] one or more segments of a newscast or sporting event.
41 (c) “Filmmaker” means a person who owns a television or film production company.
42 (d) “Local filmmaker” means a person who owns a television or film production company that
43 has its principal place of business in this state.
44 (e) “Local media production project” means, if made or performed by a local media production
45 services company, a single interactive video game or a portion thereof, a commercial or
[2]

SB 1510
1 postproduction services for a single film.
2 (f) “Local media production services company” means a media production services company that
3 has its principal place of business in this state.
4 (g) “Media production services” includes postproduction services and interactive video game
5 development. “Media production services” does not include the production of [a commercial or] one
6 or more segments of a newscast or sporting event.
7 (h) “Media production services company” means a person who is engaged in media production
8 services.
9 (i) “Portland metropolitan zone” means the area within a 30-mile radius of the center of the
10 Burnside Bridge in Portland.
11 (j) “Resident of this state” has the meaning given that term in ORS 316.027.
12 (2)(a) The Oregon Business Development Department may reimburse a filmmaker or local media
13 production services company for a portion of the actual Oregon expenses incurred by the filmmaker
14 or local media production services company.
15 (b) Maximum reimbursement for a single film or a single local media production project shall
16 be the total of:
17 (A) 20 percent of payments made for employee salaries, wages and benefits for work done in
18 Oregon; and
19 (B) 25 percent of all other actual Oregon expenses.
20 (c) Notwithstanding paragraph (b) of this subsection, maximum reimbursement for a single film
21 may not exceed 50 percent of total moneys received by the Oregon Production Investment Fund
22 during the biennium in which the actual Oregon expenses are incurred.
23 (d) To qualify for reimbursement under this subsection, total actual Oregon expenses for a film
24 or a local media production project must equal or exceed $1 million.
25 (3)(a) The department may reimburse a local filmmaker or local media production services
26 company for all or a portion of the actual Oregon expenses, up to $1 million, incurred by the local
27 filmmaker or local media production services company.
28 (b) To qualify for reimbursement under this subsection:
29 (A) Total actual Oregon expenses paid for the film or media production services must be at least
30 $75,000;
31 (B) The local filmmaker or local media production services company must have spent 80 percent
32 of the film’s payroll on employees who are residents of this state; and
33 (C) The local filmmaker or local media production services company may have employed or
34 contracted with a certified public accountant licensed by the Oregon Board of Accountancy for the
35 provision of payroll services.
36 (4) In combination with the reimbursements allowed under subsections (2) and (3) of this section,
37 the department may make an additional payment to a filmmaker for one of the following:
38 (a) A travel and living expenses rebate of $200 per employee per day, for any day that a film is
39 shot in Oregon but entirely outside the Portland metropolitan zone, not to exceed $10,000 per day
40 or $50,000 per film; or
41 (b) An increase of 10 percent of the amount otherwise allowable under subsections (2) and (3)
42 of this section, if for at least six days and at least one day more than half of its total shoot days in
43 Oregon the film is shot entirely outside the Portland metropolitan zone.
44 (5) Reimbursement under this section shall be made from moneys credited to or deposited in the
45 Oregon Production Investment Fund during the biennium in which the actual Oregon expenses were
