16 SECTION 5. The amendments to ORS 284.368 by section 4 of this 2026 Act apply to fiscal
17 years beginning on or after July 1, 2026.
18 SECTION 6. ORS 307.162 is amended to read:
19 307.162. (1)(a) Before any real or personal property may be exempted from taxation under ORS
20 307.092, 307.110 (3)(h), 307.115, 307.118, 307.130 to 307.140, 307.145, 307.147, 307.150, 307.160, 307.181
21 (3), 307.513, 307.555 or 307.580 for any tax year, the institution, organization or person entitled to
22 claim the exemption must file a claim with the county assessor, on or before April 1 preceding the
23 tax year for which the exemption is claimed. The claim must contain statements, verified by the
24 oath or affirmation of the president or other proper officer of the institution or organization or the
25 person, that:
26 (A) List all real property claimed to be exempt and show the purpose for which the real property
27 is used; and
28 (B) Cite the statutes under which exemption for personal property is claimed.
29 (b)(A) Notwithstanding paragraph (a) of this subsection, a claim for an initial year of exemption
30 under ORS 307.140 (4) must be filed with the Department of Revenue.
31 (B) If the ownership of all property, other than property described in ORS 307.110 (3)(h)[,] or
32 307.140 (4) [or 307.555], included in the claim filed with the county assessor for a prior year remains
33 unchanged, a new claim is not required.
34 (c) When the property designated in the claim for exemption is acquired after March 1 and be-
35 fore July 1, the claim for that year must be filed within 30 days from the date of acquisition of the
36 property.
37 (2)(a) Notwithstanding subsection (1) of this section, a claim may be filed under this section for
38 the current tax year:
39 (A) On or before December 31 of the tax year, if the claim is accompanied by a late filing fee
40 of the greater of $200, or one-tenth of one percent of the real market value as of the most recent
41 assessment date of the property to which the claim pertains.
42 (B) On or before April 1 of the tax year, if the claim is accompanied by a late filing fee of $200
43 and the claimant demonstrates good and sufficient cause for failing to file a timely claim, is a
44 first-time filer or is a public entity described in ORS 307.090.
45 (b)(A) Notwithstanding subsection (1) of this section, a claimant that demonstrates good and
[4]

SB 1510
1 sufficient cause for failing to file a timely claim, is a first-time filer or is a public entity described
2 in ORS 307.090 may file a claim under this section for the five tax years prior to the current tax
3 year:
4 (i) Within 60 days after the date on which the county assessor mails notice of additional taxes
5 owing under ORS 311.206 for the property to which the claim filed under this subparagraph pertains;
6 or
7 (ii) At any time if no notice is mailed.
8 (B) A claim filed under this paragraph must be accompanied by a late filing fee of the greater
9 of $200, or one-tenth of one percent of the real market value as of the most recent assessment date
10 of the property to which the claim pertains, multiplied by the number of prior tax years for which
11 exemption is claimed.
12 (c) If a claim filed under this subsection is not accompanied by the late filing fee or if the late
13 filing fee is not otherwise paid, an exemption may not be allowed for the tax years sought by the
14 claim. A claim may be filed under this subsection notwithstanding that there are no grounds for
15 hardship as required for late filing under ORS 307.475.
16 (d) The value of the property used to determine the late filing fee under this subsection and the
17 determination of the county assessor relative to a claim of good and sufficient cause are appealable
18 in the same manner as other acts of the county assessor.
19 (e) A late filing fee collected under this subsection must be deposited in the county general fund.
20 (3)(a) In a claim for exemption of property described in ORS 307.110 (3)(h), the county or city,
21 town or other municipal corporation or political subdivision of this state that is filing the claim must
22 substantiate that the property is used for affordable housing or that it is leased or rented to persons
23 of lower income, as applicable.
24 (b) A claim filed under this subsection must be filed annually on a form prescribed by the De-
25 partment of Revenue.
26 (4) As used in this section:
27 (a) “First-time filer” means a claimant that:
28 (A) Has never filed a claim for the property that is the subject of the current claim; and
29 (B) Did not receive notice from the county assessor on or before December 1 of the tax year for
30 which exemption is claimed regarding the potential property tax liability of the property.
31 (b)(A) “Good and sufficient cause” means an extraordinary circumstance beyond the control of
32 the taxpayer or the taxpayer’s agent or representative that causes the failure to file a timely claim.
33 (B) “Good and sufficient cause” does not include hardship, reliance on misleading information
34 unless the information is provided by an authorized tax official in the course of the official’s duties,
35 lack of knowledge, oversight or inadvertence.
36 (c) “Ownership” means legal and equitable title.
37 (5)(a) Notwithstanding subsection (1) of this section, if an institution or organization owns
38 property that is exempt from taxation under a provision of law listed in subsection (1) of this section
39 and fails to file a timely claim for exemption under subsection (1) of this section for additions or
40 improvements to the exempt property, the additions or improvements may nevertheless qualify for
41 exemption.
42 (b) The organization must file a claim for exemption with the county assessor to have the addi-
43 tions or improvements to the exempt property be exempt from taxation. The claim must:
44 (A) Describe the additions or improvements to the exempt property;
45 (B) Describe the current use of the property that is the subject of the application;
[5]

SB 1510
1 (C) Identify the tax year and any preceding tax years for which the exemption is sought;
2 (D) Contain any other information required by the department; and
3 (E) Be accompanied by a late filing fee equal to the product of the number of tax years for
4 which exemption is sought multiplied by the greater of $200 or one-tenth of one percent of the real
5 market value as of the most recent assessment date of the property that is the subject of the claim.
6 (c) Upon the county assessor’s receipt of a completed claim and late filing fee, the assessor shall
7 determine for each tax year for which exemption is sought whether the additions or improvements
8 that are the subject of the claim would have qualified for exemption had a timely claim been filed
9 under subsection (1) of this section. Any property that would have qualified for exemption had a
10 timely claim been filed under subsection (1) of this section is exempt from taxation for each tax year
11 for which the property would have qualified.
12 (d) A claim for exemption under this subsection may be filed only for tax years for which the
13 time for filing a claim under subsections (1) and (2)(a) of this section has expired. A claim filed under
14 this subsection, however, may serve as the claim required under subsection (1) of this section for
15 the current tax year.
16 (e) A late filing fee collected under this subsection must be deposited in the county general fund.
17 (6) For each tax year for which an exemption granted pursuant to subsection (2) or (5) of this
18 section applies:
19 (a) Any tax, or interest attributable thereto, that was paid with respect to the property that is
20 declared exempt from taxation must be refunded. Refunds must be made without interest from the
21 unsegregated tax collections account established under ORS 311.385.
22 (b) Any tax, or interest attributable thereto, that remains unpaid as of the date the exemption
23 is granted must be abated.
24 (7) If an institution, organization or person owns property that is exempt from taxation under
25 a provision of law listed in subsection (1) of this section and changes the use of the property to a
26 use that would not entitle the property to exemption from taxation, the institution or organization
27 must notify the county assessor of the change to a taxable use within 30 days.
28 SECTION 7. The amendments to ORS 307.162 by section 6 of this 2026 Act apply to
29 property tax years beginning on or after July 1, 2027.
30 SECTION 8. This 2026 Act takes effect on the 91st day after the date on which the 2026
31 regular session of the Eighty-third Legislative Assembly adjourns sine die.
